<paragraph blockId="2.[166,1225,314,725]" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">
Diagnosis. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[378,466,442,468]" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">Female</emphasis>
differs from similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Collin, 1939" authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[707,954,442,469]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[707,805,442,468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">B. pilosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Collin, J. E." box="[811,954,442,469]" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" pagination="104 - 109" refId="ref4593" refString="Collin, J. E. 1939. Notes on Syrphidae (Diptera) III. The Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 75, 104 - 109." type="journal article" year="1939">Collin, 1939</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[967,1062,442,469]" captionStart="Figs 3–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" captionTargetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetId="figure-317@2.[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 3–8. Females of Brachyopa plena (FIgs 3–5) and B. pilosa (from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">FIgs 6–8</figureCitation>
) by the larger and more ventral sensory pit on the basoflagellomere (distance between ventral edge of the pit and ventral edge of the basoflagellomere less than the diameter of the pit, as on 
<figureCitation box="[1156,1215,506,533]" captionStart="Figs 3–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" captionTargetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetId="figure-317@2.[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 3–8. Females of Brachyopa plena (FIgs 3–5) and B. pilosa (from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">FIg. 5</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[208,307,538,564]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[208,307,538,564]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">B. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, distance between ventral edge of the pit and ventral edge of the basoflagellomere exceeds the diameter of the pit, as on 
<figureCitation box="[676,734,570,597]" captionStart="Figs 3–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" captionTargetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetId="figure-317@2.[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 3–8. Females of Brachyopa plena (FIgs 3–5) and B. pilosa (from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">FIg. 8</figureCitation>
), and numerous black hairs on the lateral margin of the second tergite (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[542,640,602,628]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[542,640,602,628]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">B. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
all hairs pale, but the males have some black hairs and its quantity is rather variable) (
<bibRefCitation author="Collin, J. E." box="[578,726,634,661]" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" pagination="104 - 109" refId="ref4593" refString="Collin, J. E. 1939. Notes on Syrphidae (Diptera) III. The Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 75, 104 - 109." type="journal article" year="1939">Collin, 1939</bibRefCitation>
; Speight, 2017). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[917,1111,634,660]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plena">
<emphasis box="[917,1111,634,660]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">Brachyopa plena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Robineau-Desvoidy, 1844" authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1844" box="[197,652,666,693]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[197,343,666,692]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">B. scutellaris</emphasis>
Robineau-Desvoidy, 
<quantity box="[596,652,666,693]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.68376" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" unit="in" value="1844.0">1844</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in having basoflagellomere with ventral location of the sensory pit (distance between ventral edge of pit and ventral edge of antennal seg-
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" startId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" targetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[166,1225,1758,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">
Figs 3–8. Females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[373,533,1758,1779]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plena">
<emphasis box="[373,533,1758,1779]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">Brachyopa plena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(FIgs 3–5) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[683,765,1758,1780]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[683,765,1758,1780]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="127">B. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
ment less than the diameter of the pit), differing by the rounded and smaller sensory pit (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1844" box="[990,1145,273,299]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[990,1145,273,299]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">B. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, basoflagellomere with normally kidney-shaped or c-shaped and larger sensory pit), and notopleuron with black and pale pile (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1844" box="[1074,1232,436,462]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[1074,1232,436,462]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">B. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually with pale pile only)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
(
<bibRefCitation author="Collin, J. E." box="[900,1048,501,528]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="104 - 109" refId="ref4593" refString="Collin, J. E. 1939. Notes on Syrphidae (Diptera) III. The Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 75, 104 - 109." type="journal article" year="1939">Collin, 1939</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref5733" refString="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identiFIcation of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens from
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" box="[892,1232,566,593]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<collectingCountry box="[892,988,566,593]" name="Ukraine" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Ukraine</collectingCountry>
have the notopleu-
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" box="[174,1201,594,626]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
Fig. 9. Male of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zetterstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[316,486,594,616]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis box="[316,486,594,616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Brachyopa vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, dorsal view. ron with a few black hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" box="[945,1233,631,658]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Additional features.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" box="[892,1233,664,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[892,1126,664,690]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plena">
<emphasis box="[892,1126,664,690]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Brachyopa plena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[174,1233,175,984]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
Zakarpattia have vertex as wide as width of the basoflagellomere (
<figureCitation box="[925,987,696,723]" captionStart="Figs 3–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" captionTargetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetId="figure-317@2.[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 3–8. Females of Brachyopa plena (FIgs 3–5) and B. pilosa (from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">FIg. 4</figureCitation>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[1135,1233,696,722]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[1135,1233,696,722]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">B. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from 
<collectingRegion box="[253,405,729,756]" country="Ukraine" name="Kyiv" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Kyiv Region</collectingRegion>
), vertex is 1.33 times as wide as basoflagellomere width (
<figureCitation box="[1098,1164,729,756]" captionStart="Figs 3–8" captionStartId="2.[166,205,1758,1780]" captionTargetBox="[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetId="figure-317@2.[277,1115,771,1726]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 3–8. Females of Brachyopa plena (FIgs 3–5) and B. pilosa (from Kyiv Region) (FIgs 6–8): 3, 6 — habitus, dorsal view; 4, 7 — head, frontal view; 5, 8 — head, anterolateral view (arrow shows the sensory pit on the basoflagellomere)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6454610" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6454610/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">FIg. 7</figureCitation>
). The specimen from Zakarpattia has the postpronotum yellowish-brown, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collin" authorityYear="1939" box="[1110,1209,761,787]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis box="[1110,1209,761,787]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">B. pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is at least dorsally black. N o t e. Speight (2017) remarks that “…the shape of this pit varies, and occasional specimens may be found, among series of specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1844" box="[782,928,859,885]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Brachyopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[782,928,859,885]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">B. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Western Europe, in which this pit is either oval or round, or of indeterminate shape”. We still admit that the specimen on hand can be an aberrant 
